Column Comment.0: UNIQUE WELL IDENTIFIER: A unique name, code or number designated as theprimary key for this row.
Column Comment.1: CURVE IDENTIFIER: Unique identification number assigned to the curve or trace.
Column Comment.2: WELL LOG CURVE AXIS IDENTIFIER: unique identifier for the axis on the well logcurve, in the case where a single curve contains multiple axis.
Column Comment.3: ACTIVE INDICATOR: A Y/N flag indicating whether this row of data is currently eitheractive / valid (Y) or inactive / invalid (N).
Column Comment.4: AXIS ORGINAL UNIT OF MEASURE: The unit of measure in which this axis wascreated. Note that this information may also be contained in the meta model.
Column Comment.5: AXIS SEQUENCE NUMBER: the order in which the axis are to occur in order tocorrectly use and manipulate the data.
Column Comment.6: AXIS UNIT OF MEASURE: The unit of measure in which this axis is stored. Note thatthis information may also be contained in the meta model.
Column Comment.7: DIMENSION COUNT: the count of the number of dimensions in this axis of the welllog curve.
Column Comment.8: EFFECTIVE DATE: The date that the data in this row first came into effect.
Column Comment.9: EXPIRY DATE: The date that the data in this row was no longer active or in effect.
Column Comment.10: ROW_MANAGEMENT_GUID: This value may be used to provide a global uniqueidentifier for this row of data. Use of this column is not mandatory, but if used,optional PPDM NOT NULL and UNIQUE INDEX constraints provided in the datamodel DDL should be created.
Column Comment.11: REMARK: Narrative remarks about this row of data.
Column Comment.12: REPORTED AXIS MNEMONIC: the mnemonic value reported for the axis. Usuallythe name or number of the secondary axis. The source for this information is RP66AXIS ID - AXIS-ID is a dictionary-controlled reference value identifying the coordinateaxis. Valid identifiers are administered in the dictionary specified by theNAMESPACE-CODE and NAMESPACE-NAME attributes of the objects origin. Thereare currently no reference values defined under the basic schema.
Column Comment.13: REPORTED AXIS OBJECT NAME: the actual name of the RP66 AXIS object. This isa general concept in RP66, and applies to any object in an RP66 data set, defined asa three-part unique reference to an object consisting of an origin,a copy number, andan identifier. The value of the object name is unconstrained (as long as it conforms tothe syntactic requirements), and uniquely identifies any object within the context of aspecific RP66 data set.
Column Comment.14: SOURCE: The individual, company, state, or government agency designated as thesource of information for this row.
Column Comment.15: SPACING: the spacing of regularly spaced elements on this axis. The spacing onsome axis may not be regular; in this case, use as many coordinate values describedin WELL LOG AXIS COORD as are available. The remainder of the axis (up to thenumberof values captured in VALUE COUNT) will be regularly spaced as describedin this column.
Column Comment.18: VALUE COUNT: the total number of non-null values found on the well log curve axix.
Column Comment.19: ROW CHANGED BY: Application login id of the user who last changed the row.
Column Comment.20: ROW CHANGED DATE: System date of the last time the row was changed.
Column Comment.21: ROW CREATED BY: System user who created this row of data.
Column Comment.22: ROW CREATED DATE: Date that the row was created on.
Column Comment.23: ROW_EFFECTIVE_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of datais effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row of data wasmade available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.24: ROW_EXPIRY_DATE: A system assigned date that specified when a row of data isno longer effective from a systems perspective. This may be the date that a row ofdata was no longer available to end users, for example.
Column Comment.25: PPDM ROW QUALITY: A set of values indicating the quality of data in this row,usually with reference to the method or procedures used to load the data, althoughother types of quality reference are permitted.
